<p>The <strong>Internet History Directory</strong> is a human-curated guide to the history of the Internet and the Web. It brings together historically important websites, primary documents, archive resources, organisations, standards bodies, online communities, and cultural artefacts that help explain how the networked world came to be.</p>
<p>The goal is not to index everything on the modern web. Instead, the directory focuses on significance, context, and long-term historical value. Some entries are surviving original sites. Others are official histories, preserved archives, scholarly resources, or later references that document services and communities that no longer exist in their original form.</p>
<p>This project is built in the spirit of the early human-edited web directory: organised by topic, maintained by hand, and designed for browsing as much as searching. It is intended for researchers, enthusiasts, students, and anyone who wants to explore the foundations of the Internet beyond the algorithmic surface of today’s web.</p>